ethics:{title:'Ethics & Professional Standards',eye:'Tested ALL 3 Levels &#8212; complexity grows each level',weights:{l1:'15&#8211;20%',l2:'10&#8211;15%',l3:'10&#8211;15%'},
  overview:'The only topic tested in full depth at all three levels. Covers the CFA Code of Ethics, 7 Standards of Professional Conduct (22 sub-standards), GIPS, and at L3, the Asset Manager Code. A special ethics adjustment can push borderline candidates to a pass.',
  notes:[
    {title:'Code of Ethics & 7 Standards',lv:['l1','l2','l3'],sum:'The 6 Code components and 7 Standards apply at all levels. L1: recognise violations. L2: apply to complex vignette scenarios. L3: write essay justifications and determine remediation.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Code of Ethics &#8212; 6 Components',lv:['l1','l2','l3'],col:'#C0392B',
          lead:'Six commitments every CFA member must uphold.',
          notes:[{t:'Components',b:'1. Act with integrity, competence, diligence, respect. 2. Place client interests above personal. 3. Use reasonable care & independent judgement. 4. Practice to reflect credit on profession. 5. Promote integrity of global capital markets. 6. Maintain and improve professional competence.'},{t:'The Hierarchy',b:'Law &#8594; Code & Standards &#8594; Employer policy. Always follow whichever is STRICTER. When uncertain about disclosure &#8212; always disclose.'},{t:'Ethics Adjustment',b:'CFA Institute may pass borderline candidates based on strong Ethics performance. Ethics is worth more than its percentage weight suggests.'}]},
        {title:'Standard I &#8212; Professionalism',lv:['l1','l2','l3'],col:'#E67E22',
          lead:'I(A) Knowledge of Law. I(B) Independence & Objectivity. I(C) Misrepresentation. I(D) Misconduct.',
          notes:[{t:'I(A) Knowledge of Law',b:'Follow the stricter of local law or Code & Standards. Ignorance of the law is not a defence. Must dissociate from known violations.'},{t:'I(B) Independence',b:'Gifts/benefits that could impair independence must be disclosed. Even small gifts require disclosure if they could influence recommendations.'},{t:'I(C) Misrepresentation',b:'No false statements. No plagiarism &#8212; must cite all sources, including other analysts\' work. No guaranteed return promises.'},{t:'I(D) Misconduct',b:'Catch-all for dishonesty or fraud in any professional context. Personal conduct (e.g. fraud outside work) can still violate this standard.'}]},
        {title:'Standard II &#8212; Capital Markets Integrity',lv:['l1','l2','l3'],col:'#2980B9',
          lead:'II(A) Material Nonpublic Information (MNPI). II(B) Market Manipulation.',
          notes:[{t:'Mosaic Theory',b:'PERMITTED: combining public information + non-material NPI to reach an investment conclusion. Only material AND nonpublic information is prohibited. Mosaic theory is a key exam concept.'},{t:'Market Manipulation',b:'Cannot spread false information OR conduct trades to create artificial prices/volume. Rumour-spreading without trading is still a violation of II(B).'}]},
        {title:'Standard III &#8212; Duties to Clients',lv:['l1','l2','l3'],col:'#27AE60',
          lead:'III(A) Loyalty. III(B) Fair Dealing. III(C) Suitability. III(D) Performance Presentation. III(E) Confidentiality.',
          notes:[{t:'Priority Order',b:'Client first &#8594; Employer second &#8594; Personal last. This is the foundational ordering for all conflicts.'},{t:'Fair vs Equal',b:'III(B) requires FAIR dealing &#8212; not identical treatment. Institutional clients may receive more detailed research; that is not a violation if all clients receive the recommendation simultaneously.'},{t:'Suitability (IPS)',b:'Must have an Investment Policy Statement for each client. Update when circumstances change. A good product sold to an unsuitable client is still a violation.'},{t:'Confidentiality Exceptions',b:'Can disclose if: client consents, law requires, or reporting a violation to CFA Institute. Otherwise maintain confidentiality of all client information.'}]},
        {title:'Standards IV&#8211;VII &#8212; Employer, Analysis, Conflicts, CFA',lv:['l1','l2','l3'],col:'#8E44AD',
          lead:'IV: Duties to Employers. V: Investment Analysis. VI: Conflicts of Interest. VII: CFA Member/Candidate.',
          notes:[{t:'IV(A) Loyalty to Employer',b:'Cannot take client lists, models, or proprietary work when leaving. Cannot set up competing firm while still employed. IV(B): outside compensation needs WRITTEN employer consent.'},{t:'V &#8212; Analysis & Records',b:'V(A): must have thorough independent basis for recommendations. V(B): separate fact from opinion in all reports. V(C): retain records minimum 7 years.'},{t:'VI &#8212; Conflicts',b:'VI(A): prominent, plain-language, timely disclosure. VI(B): client first, no front-running. VI(C): disclose all referral fees regardless of whether referral is genuinely good.'},{t:'VII &#8212; CFA Designation',b:'No partial CFA designation. Cannot say "CFA Level 1 Candidate" after passing Level 1. Can say "passed Level 1 of the CFA exam." Cannot imply CFA guarantees superior performance.'}]},
        {title:'GIPS Standards',lv:['l1','l3'],col:'#2C3E50',
          lead:'L1: conceptual introduction. L3: fully tested &#8212; return calculations, composites, presentation, verification.',
          notes:[{t:'Core GIPS Rules',b:'Compliance is FIRM-WIDE only. Cannot claim for one product or strategy. Must include ALL fee-paying discretionary accounts in at least one composite. Terminated accounts stay in historical composites &#8212; no survivorship bias.'},{t:'Return Calculations',b:'TWR (time-weighted return) required &#8212; eliminates effect of external cash flows. MWR/IRR permitted for PE and real estate where manager controls cash flow timing.'},{t:'Presentation Requirements',b:'Minimum 5 years of annual returns, building to 10. Must disclose: number of portfolios, composite assets as % of firm assets, measure of dispersion. Verification is optional but recommended.'}]},
        {title:'Asset Manager Code (L3 only)',lv:['l3'],col:'#16A085',
          lead:'Firm-level ethics code &#8212; 6 principles for investment management companies. Distinct from Standards which apply to individuals.',
          notes:[{t:'6 Principles',b:'1. Loyalty to clients. 2. Investment process & actions. 3. Trading (no MNPI, client priority before firm trades). 4. Compliance & support. 5. Performance & valuation. 6. Disclosures. Voluntary adoption. Signals firm-level commitment to ethics.'},{t:'Code vs Standards',b:'Asset Manager Code = firm level. Code & Standards = individual level. Both can apply simultaneously to the same situation.'}]},
        {title:'L2 Additional Standards',lv:['l2'],col:'#E74C3C',
          lead:'Three standards introduced at Level 2: Soft Dollar Standard, Research Objectivity Standard, Prudent Investor Rule.',
          notes:[{t:'Soft Dollar Standard',b:'Using client brokerage commissions to pay for research is permitted ONLY if the research primarily benefits the client. Cannot use for firm overhead. Must disclose all soft dollar arrangements.'},{t:'Research Objectivity Standard',b:'Analyst independence from investment banking pressure. Firms must separate research from banking. No pre-publication sharing with banking clients. Quiet periods around IPOs.'},{t:'Required vs Recommended',b:'EXAM TRAP: failing to follow a Recommended procedure is NOT a violation. Only Required procedures create obligations. Know which is which &#8212; many exam questions test this distinction.'}]},
      ]
    }
