quant:{title:'Quantitative Methods',eye:'Tested L1 & L2 &#183; Applied in Portfolio Mgmt at L3',weights:{l1:'6&#8211;9%',l2:'5&#8211;10%',l3:'N/A'},
  overview:'Mathematical and statistical tools underpinning all investment analysis. L1: TVM, statistics, probability, hypothesis testing, simple regression. L2: multiple regression with violations, time series, machine learning. L3: assumed knowledge applied within Portfolio Management.',
  notes:[
    {title:'Time Value of Money (L1)',lv:['l1'],sum:'Foundation of all valuation. Must be mastered on the financial calculator. TVM is tested in every topic that involves valuation.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'TVM Core Calculations',lv:['l1'],col:'#E67E22',lead:'PV, FV, PMT, N, I/Y. Annuity types. Perpetuity. EAR vs APR.',
          notes:[{t:'Key Formulas',b:'Annuity ordinary: payments at END of period. Annuity due: payments at START &#8212; multiply ordinary PV &#215; (1+r). Perpetuity: PV = PMT/r. EAR = (1+APR/m)^m &#8722; 1. Continuous compounding: FV = PV &#215; e^(r&#215;t).'},{t:'Calculator Tip',b:'Check BGN/END mode before annuity due problems. Forgetting to switch to BGN mode is the most common TVM error. Practice switching modes until automatic.'}]}
      ]
    },
    {title:'Statistics & Probability (L1)',lv:['l1'],sum:'Descriptive statistics, probability theory, and distributions that underpin hypothesis testing and portfolio mathematics.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Descriptive Statistics',lv:['l1'],col:'#2980B9',lead:'Mean types, dispersion measures, skewness, kurtosis.',
          notes:[{t:'Mean Types',b:'Arithmetic: simple average &#8212; use for expected value calculations. Geometric: use for multi-period investment returns (always less than arithmetic). Harmonic: use for averaging P/E ratios and other ratio averages.'},{t:'Distribution Shape',b:'Positive skew: right tail; mean > median > mode. Leptokurtic: fat tails (excess kurtosis > 0) &#8212; more extreme outcomes than normal. Platykurtic: thin tails.'}]},
        {title:'Normal Distribution & Hypothesis Testing',lv:['l1'],col:'#C0392B',lead:'Normal distribution properties. Type I/II errors. p-values.',
          notes:[{t:'Normal Distribution',b:'68% within &#177;1&#963;, 95% within &#177;2&#963;, 99% within &#177;3&#963;. Critical z-values: 1.645 (10%), 1.96 (5%), 2.576 (1%) two-tailed. Use Student\'s t when population variance unknown.'},{t:'Error Types',b:'Type I error (&#945; = significance level): reject a TRUE null = false positive. Type II error (&#946;): fail to reject a FALSE null = false negative. Cannot minimise both simultaneously &#8212; reducing &#945; increases &#946;.'},{t:'Decision Rule',b:'Reject H&#8320; if p-value < &#945;. Or if |test statistic| > critical value. p-value = probability of observing a result this extreme IF the null were true.'}]}
      ]
    },
    {title:'Regression Analysis (L1/L2)',lv:['l1','l2'],sum:'Simple regression (L1) and multiple regression with violations and remedies (L2). Core analytical tool for investment research.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Simple & Multiple Regression',lv:['l1','l2'],col:'#8E44AD',lead:'Y = b&#8320; + b&#8321;X&#8321; + ... + b&#8345;X&#8345; + &#949;. F-test and t-tests. R&#178; vs Adjusted R&#178;.',
          notes:[{t:'Key Statistics',b:'R&#178;: proportion of Y variance explained by X. Adjusted R&#178;: penalises adding irrelevant variables &#8212; always use to compare models. F-test: tests if ALL coefficients jointly zero. t-test: tests each coefficient individually.'},{t:'Regression Output',b:'SEE (standard error of estimate): measures forecast accuracy. Large SEE = large prediction errors. Confidence interval for prediction: b&#8321; &#177; t_critical &#215; SE(b&#8321;).'}]},
        {title:'Regression Violations (L2)',lv:['l2'],col:'#E67E22',lead:'Heteroskedasticity, autocorrelation, multicollinearity. Detecting and fixing each.',
          notes:[{t:'Heteroskedasticity',b:'Non-constant variance of residuals. Detect: Breusch-Pagan test. Effect: standard errors wrong &#8594; t-stats unreliable (may seem significant when not). Fix: use White/robust standard errors.'},{t:'Autocorrelation',b:'Correlated residuals (common in time series). Detect: Durbin-Watson test (DW &#8776; 2 = no autocorrelation; DW < 2 = positive; DW > 2 = negative). Fix: Newey-West standard errors.'},{t:'Multicollinearity',b:'Correlated predictor variables. Effect: inflates standard errors, reduces t-stats &#8594; variables appear insignificant. Detect: high VIF or pairwise correlations. Fix: remove one of the correlated variables.'}]}
      ]
    },
    {title:'Time Series & Machine Learning (L2)',lv:['l2'],sum:'AR models for forecasting financial data. Machine learning techniques increasingly applied in investment analysis.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Time Series &#8212; AR Models',lv:['l2'],col:'#16A085',lead:'AR(1) model, covariance stationarity, unit root problem, mean reversion.',
          notes:[{t:'AR(1) Model',b:'x&#8348; = b&#8320; + b&#8321;x&#8348;&#8331;&#8321; + &#949;&#8348;. Covariance-stationary requires: constant mean, constant variance, constant covariances. Mean reversion level = b&#8320;/(1&#8722;b&#8321;).'},{t:'Unit Root Problem',b:'If b&#8321; = 1 &#8594; random walk &#8594; non-stationary &#8594; standard regression produces spurious results. Test: augmented Dickey-Fuller. Fix: first-difference the series (use changes not levels).'}]},
        {title:'Machine Learning Overview',lv:['l2'],col:'#2C3E50',lead:'Supervised vs unsupervised learning. Regularisation. Alternative data. Overfitting.',
          notes:[{t:'Learning Types',b:'Supervised (labelled data): regression, classification trees, neural networks. Unsupervised (unlabelled): clustering, PCA. Reinforcement: reward-based. Finance applications: credit scoring, fraud detection, factor extraction.'},{t:'Regularisation',b:'LASSO (L1 penalty): shrinks some coefficients to exactly zero &#8594; feature selection. Ridge (L2 penalty): shrinks all coefficients but not to zero &#8594; reduces multicollinearity. Both reduce overfitting.'},{t:'Overfitting Risk',b:'Model fits training data too perfectly &#8594; fails on new data. Use out-of-sample testing. Alternative data (satellite imagery, NLP, credit card transactions) introduces look-ahead bias risk if not managed carefully.'}]}
      ]
    },
  ],
