pm:{title:'Portfolio Management',eye:'L1: Intro &#183; L2: Advanced &#183; L3: Dominant (40%+)',weights:{l1:'8&#8211;12%',l2:'10&#8211;15%',l3:'40%+'},
  overview:'The culminating topic of the entire CFA program. L1: Markowitz, CAPM, IPS basics, behavioural finance. L2: multifactor models, active management theory. L3: everything comes together &#8212; asset allocation, portfolio construction, client management, performance measurement.',
  notes:[
    {title:'Markowitz & CAPM (L1)',lv:['l1'],sum:'Modern portfolio theory and the Capital Asset Pricing Model &#8212; the theoretical foundation of all portfolio management.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Markowitz & Efficient Frontier',lv:['l1'],col:'#2980B9',lead:'Efficient frontier: maximum return for given risk. Diversification reduces portfolio variance when correlation < 1.',
          notes:[{t:'Portfolio Variance',b:'&#963;&#178;p = w&#8321;&#178;&#963;&#8321;&#178; + w&#8322;&#178;&#963;&#8322;&#178; + 2w&#8321;w&#8322;&#961;&#963;&#8321;&#963;&#8322;. As n&#8594;&#8734;: portfolio variance approaches average covariance (systematic risk). Idiosyncratic risk diversified away.'},{t:'Key Insight',b:'Only systematic risk is compensated. Idiosyncratic (company-specific) risk is FREE to eliminate through diversification &#8212; investors are NOT paid for taking unnecessary risk.'}]},
        {title:'CAPM & SML',lv:['l1'],col:'#C0392B',lead:'E(Ri) = Rf + &#946;i(Rm&#8722;Rf). Beta = Cov(i,m)/Var(m). SML plots expected return vs beta for all assets.',
          notes:[{t:'SML vs CML',b:'CML: uses total risk (&#963;) &#8212; applies only to efficient portfolios (on the frontier). SML: uses beta (systematic risk) &#8212; applies to ALL assets including individual securities.'},{t:'Risk-Adjusted Measures',b:'Sharpe = (Rp&#8722;Rf)/&#963; (total risk &#8212; for standalone). Treynor = (Rp&#8722;Rf)/&#946; (systematic risk &#8212; when one of many portfolios). Jensen\'s alpha = actual &#8722; CAPM expected return.'}]},
        {title:'Investment Policy Statement',lv:['l1','l2','l3'],col:'#27AE60',lead:'Documents return objective, risk tolerance (ability AND willingness), and five constraints (TTLLL).',
          notes:[{t:'Risk Rule',b:'Ability to take risk (financial: time horizon, income stability, liquidity) vs Willingness (psychological: comfort with volatility). When they conflict &#8594; always use the LOWER of the two.'},{t:'Constraints',b:'Time horizon, Taxes, Liquidity, Legal/regulatory, Unique circumstances. Must address all five for a complete IPS. Update IPS when any constraint changes materially.'}]},
      ]
    },
    {title:'Multifactor Models & Active Mgmt (L2)',lv:['l2'],sum:'Beyond CAPM: factor models explaining more return variation. The Fundamental Law of Active Management.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Fama-French & Factor Models',lv:['l2'],col:'#8E44AD',lead:'Market + SMB (size) + HML (value) + WML (momentum). Factors explain most active return variation.',
          notes:[{t:'Key Factors',b:'SMB (Small Minus Big): small-cap size premium. HML (High Minus Low book-to-market): value premium. WML (Winners Minus Losers): momentum premium. Most "alpha" disappears once factor exposures are properly accounted for.'},{t:'Practical Implication',b:'Regress portfolio returns on factors to decompose into factor exposures vs true alpha. Most active manager alpha is really just factor tilt (value, small cap, momentum) that can be replicated cheaply via smart beta.'}]},
        {title:'Fundamental Law of Active Management',lv:['l2','l3'],col:'#16A085',lead:'IR = IC &#215; &#8730;BR. Only two ways to improve: get more skilled (IC) or make more independent bets (BR).',
          notes:[{t:'Components',b:'IC (Information Coefficient): correlation between forecasts and outcomes = skill. BR (Breadth): number of independent investment decisions per year. IR = active return / tracking error = reward per unit of active risk.'},{t:'Implications',b:'Specialised manager (high IC, low BR) can match broad manager (low IC, high BR). Most active managers have IC barely above zero &#8212; after fees, most underperform. High fees are the biggest barrier to active management value creation.'}]},
      ]
    },
    {title:'Asset Allocation (L3)',lv:['l3'],sum:'The most important single investment decision. SAA, TAA, rebalancing, and advanced allocation frameworks.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'SAA, TAA & Rebalancing',lv:['l3'],col:'#2980B9',lead:'SAA: long-term policy weights. TAA: short-term tilts. Rebalancing: calendar vs corridor.',
          notes:[{t:'SAA',b:'Based on investor objectives, risk tolerance, and constraints. Research shows 90%+ of return variability explained by asset allocation, not security selection. Review every 3&#8211;5 years or when circumstances change materially.'},{t:'Rebalancing',b:'Calendar: fixed schedule (monthly, quarterly). Corridor/threshold: rebalance when weights drift beyond bands. Wider corridors for: high transaction costs, low asset volatility, high risk tolerance, positively correlated assets.'}]},
        {title:'Black-Litterman & Risk Parity',lv:['l3'],col:'#C0392B',lead:'BL overcomes MVO instability. Risk parity allocates by risk contribution, not capital weight.',
          notes:[{t:'Black-Litterman',b:'Problem: MVO is extremely sensitive to expected return inputs &#8212; small changes cause extreme weight swings. BL solution: use market cap equilibrium returns as prior, then tilt toward investor views with specified confidence. Output: stable, diversified allocations.'},{t:'Risk Parity',b:'Each asset contributes equally to total portfolio risk. Result: large fixed income allocation (bonds have low vol). Often levered to achieve equity-like returns. Diversifies risk factors more evenly than cap-weighted allocation.'}]},
        {title:'Liability-Relative & Goals-Based',lv:['l3'],col:'#27AE60',lead:'LDI for institutions managing liabilities. Goals-based for private clients with specific objectives.',
          notes:[{t:'LDI &#8212; DB Pensions',b:'Surplus = Assets &#8722; PV(Liabilities). Hedging portfolio: matches liability duration + inflation sensitivity (long bonds, rate swaps). Return-seeking: targets excess returns to grow surplus (equities, alternatives). Immunisation: match asset duration to liability duration.'},{t:'Goals-Based',b:'Prioritise goals: essential (retirement income) &#8594; aspirational (vacation home). Each goal = sub-portfolio with appropriate risk. Mental accounting used constructively. Effective for behavioural anchoring of private clients.'}]},
      ]
    },
    {title:'Performance Measurement (L3)',lv:['l3'],sum:'Attribution analysis, risk-adjusted measures, GIPS, and manager evaluation frameworks.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Brinson Attribution Model',lv:['l3'],col:'#E67E22',lead:'Active return = Allocation effect + Selection effect + Interaction effect.',
          notes:[{t:'Components',b:'Allocation: did you overweight/underweight sectors correctly? Selection: did you pick better securities within each sector? Interaction: joint effect of timing and selection decisions. Allocation and selection measure two distinct decision-making activities.'},{t:'Practical Use',b:'Attribution tells portfolio managers WHERE they added or lost value. Use to: identify skill vs luck, assess consistency, guide future process improvements.'}]},
        {title:'Risk-Adjusted Performance Measures',lv:['l1','l2','l3'],col:'#2C3E50',lead:'Sharpe, Treynor, Jensen\'s alpha, Information Ratio, M&#178;, Appraisal Ratio.',
          notes:[{t:'Which Measure to Use',b:'Sharpe: use when evaluating a standalone portfolio (uses total risk &#963;). Treynor: use when portfolio is one of many (uses beta). IR: use for benchmark-relative comparison (active return / tracking error). Jensen\'s alpha: use for absolute excess return vs CAPM.'},{t:'M&#178;',b:'M&#178; = Sharpe &#215; &#963;_market + Rf. Converts Sharpe ratio to a return figure for intuitive comparison. M&#178; > market return = outperformed on risk-adjusted basis.'}]},
      ]
    },
  ],
