pw_p:{title:'L3 Pathway: Private Wealth',eye:'Level 3 Specialised Pathway &#183; 30&#8211;35% of exam',weights:{l1:'&#8212;',l2:'&#8212;',l3:'30&#8211;35%'},
  overview:'For private bankers, wealth advisors, and family office professionals. Covers HNW individuals and families: personalised IPS construction, tax planning, estate planning, wealth transfer, behavioural coaching.',
  notes:[
    {title:'Human Capital & Client Profiling',lv:['l3'],sum:'Understanding the full financial picture of a private client. Total wealth = human capital + financial capital.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Human Capital in Portfolio Planning',lv:['l3'],col:'#E67E22',lead:'Bond-like human capital &#8594; equity-heavy portfolio. Equity-like human capital &#8594; bond-heavy portfolio.',
          notes:[{t:'Life-Cycle Approach',b:'Young: large human capital, small financial capital &#8594; take equity risk. Older: human capital depleted &#8594; shift to income/bonds. Risk capacity naturally declines with age as future earning power diminishes.'},{t:'Human Capital Type',b:'Bond-like (stable salaried: academic, civil servant): financial portfolio can be equity-heavy for diversification. Equity-like (variable income: entrepreneur, banker whose income correlates with markets): financial portfolio should be bond-heavy.'}]},
        {title:'Private Client IPS Construction',lv:['l3'],col:'#2980B9',lead:'More personalised than institutional IPS. Multiple time horizons, tax status, behavioural factors.',
          notes:[{t:'Components',b:'Return objective: required (to meet essential goals) + aspirational. Risk: ability vs willingness &#8212; use lower. Time horizons: one per distinct goal (retirement, education, purchase). Liquidity events: known future cash needs. Tax status: marginal rate, treatment of investment income. Unique: concentrated position, ethical screens, family dynamics.'},{t:'Behavioural Biases',b:'Private clients are more susceptible than institutions. Common: loss aversion (hold losers too long), overconfidence (underdiversify), anchoring (fixate on purchase price), home bias. Use goals-based framing and systematic rebalancing to overcome.'}]}
      ]
    },
    {title:'Tax Planning',lv:['l3'],sum:'Minimising lifetime tax burden through account selection, asset location, and realisation strategy.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Tax Types & After-Tax Returns',lv:['l3'],col:'#27AE60',lead:'Accrual tax reduces compounding base annually. Capital gains deferral creates compounding benefit.',
          notes:[{t:'Tax Drag',b:'Accrual tax (income, dividends): paid annually &#8594; reduces compounding base every year. Capital gains tax: paid on realisation &#8594; deferral benefit: unpaid tax amount compounds until sale. Even at same ultimate tax rate, deferral creates significant value over long horizons.'},{t:'Tax-Loss Harvesting',b:'Realise losses to offset capital gains, reducing current-year tax. Immediately reinvest in similar (but not identical) assets to maintain portfolio exposure. Mind wash-sale rules. Effective only in taxable accounts.'}]},
        {title:'Asset Location Strategy',lv:['l3'],col:'#C0392B',lead:'Tax-exempt accounts: highest-return assets. Tax-deferred: bonds/income. Taxable: low-turnover index funds.',
          notes:[{t:'Optimal Location',b:'Tax-exempt (ISA, Roth): highest expected return assets &#8212; tax-free growth most valuable here. Tax-deferred (pension, 401k): bonds, REITs, high-yield, high-turnover active &#8212; income eventually taxed but deferral helps. Taxable: broad low-turnover index funds, growth stocks held long-term.'},{t:'Practical Rule',b:'A bond earning 4% in a tax-exempt account is worth more than a bond earning 4% in a taxable account. Match asset tax-efficiency to account tax treatment.'}]}
      ]
    },
    {title:'Estate Planning & Wealth Transfer',lv:['l3'],sum:'Transferring wealth efficiently to heirs and charitable causes while managing estate taxes.',
      kcs:[
        {title:'Gifting & Stepped-Up Basis',lv:['l3'],col:'#8E44AD',lead:'Stepped-up basis at death eliminates embedded capital gains. Gifting reduces taxable estate.',
          notes:[{t:'Stepped-Up Basis',b:'At death, inherited assets reset to fair market value &#8212; all embedded capital gains tax eliminated. Holding appreciated assets until death (rather than gifting them) can be tax-optimal if estate is not subject to inheritance tax. Compare: gift &#163;500k asset with &#163;200k gain vs inherit it.'},{t:'Gifting',b:'Annual gift exclusion (US 2024: $18k per recipient) reduces taxable estate without gift tax. Donate appreciated stock to charity: deduct full market value AND avoid capital gains &#8212; double tax benefit.'}]},
        {title:'Trusts & Structures',lv:['l3'],col:'#16A085',lead:'Revocable (no tax benefit), irrevocable (removes from estate), GRAT, QTIP, generation-skipping.',
          notes:[{t:'Trust Types',b:'Revocable: grantor retains control, avoids probate, no estate tax benefit. Irrevocable: removes assets from estate, tax benefit, grantor loses control. GRAT: transfer asset growth to heirs tax-efficiently if asset appreciates above hurdle rate. Generation-skipping trust: bypasses estate tax at child\'s death, passes directly to grandchildren.'}]}
      ]
    },
  ],
  outcomes:{objective:'Design comprehensive wealth strategies for HNW individuals and families: investment policy, tax optimisation, estate planning, and behavioural coaching.',
